Title : David Rowe (entrepreneur)
Text : {{Other people|David Rowe}}
'''David Rowe''' (born 1958) is a London based high tech entrepreneur who founded [[Easynet]],<ref>http://startups.co.uk/easynet-david-rowe/</ref><ref name="David Rowe: European Easy Rider">[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/business/analysis-and-features/david-rowe-european-easy-rider-694101.html David Rowe: European Easy Rider]</ref>  a U.K. ISP in 1994, alongside [[Cyberia, London|Cyberia]], one of the worlds first commercial [[cybercafe]]s.   Easynet was one of the first Internet companies in the U.K.  to list on [[Alternative Investment Market|AIM]] in 1996, and subsequently on the [[London Stock Exchange|LSE]] in 1999.<ref>http://www.telecompaper.com/news/easynet-to-be-listed-on-main-london-stock-exchange--166915</ref> The company created subsidiaries in a number of European countries and pioneered alternative [[Local-loop unbundling|local loop infrastructure]] in the UK.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.computerweekly.com/feature/Easynet-encroach-into-BTs-last-mile |title=Easynet encroach into BT's last mile |work=[[Computer Weekly]] |date=January 2001|accessdate=2015-07-22 }}</ref>  In 2001 Easynet merged with [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/2723770/Marconi-agrees-357m-shares-deal-for-Ipsaris-with-Easynet.html Ipsaris], the U.K. fibre optic infrastructure provider owned by [[Marconi Communications|Marconi]]. In 2006 Easynet was bought by [[BSkyB]] for £211m<ref name=Deans2005 >{{cite news
 |title =
BSkyB buys Easynet for £211m
 |last = Deans
 |first = Jason
 |date = 21 October 2005
 |newspaper = The Guardian
 |url = https://www.theguardian.com/media/2005/oct/21/television.digitalmedia}}</ref> and Rowe worked for [[James Murdoch]] as part of the Sky management team.  In 2010, Rowe led the buyout team of Easynet Corporate services from Sky alongside [[Lloyds Devel|LDC]], a UK [[private equity]] company owned by [[Lloyds Bank]].<ref>http://www.globaltelecomsbusiness.com/Article/2635798/Search/Results/Bank-buys-Easynet-from-Murdoch.html?Keywords=Easynet#.U33cZl5N1Fw</ref>

Rowe left Easynet to start his own high tech [[venture capital]] business [http://www.blackgreencapital.com Black Green Capital] in 2013.<ref name=Crouch2014 >{{cite news
 |title = UK firm takes the cloud to chillier climes with Swedish data centre
 |last = Crouch
 |first = David
 |date = 22 October 2014
 |newspaper = The Guardian
 |url = https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2014/oct/22/cloud-storage-data-centre-sweden-arctic-hydro66 }}</ref>

Rowe was selected by the [[National Portrait Gallery, London|National Portrait Gallery]] for entrepreneurship in Telecoms and the Internet.<ref>http://www.npg.org.uk/collections/search/person/mp72197/david-rowe?search=sas&sText=david+rowe</ref>

